"Williamson C.E., Saros J.E., Vincent W.F., Smol J.P.","Lakes and reservoirs as sentinels, integrators, and regulators of climate change",2009,"Limnology and Oceanography","54","6 PART 2",,"2273","2282",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77956241535&partnerID=40&md5=5f54d311c05cc4f56c6b75a559d68cdd","Department of Zoology, Miami University, Oxford, OH, United States; Climate Change Institute, School of Biology and Ecology, University of Maine, Orono, ME, United States; Centre for Northern Studies (CEN), Laval University, Quebec City, QC, Canada; Paleoecological Environmental Assessment and Research Lab (PEARL), Department of Biology, Queen's University, Kingston, ON, Canada","Williamson, C.E., Department of Zoology, Miami University, Oxford, OH, United States; Saros, J.E., Climate Change Institute, School of Biology and Ecology, University of Maine, Orono, ME, United States; Vincent, W.F., Centre for Northern Studies (CEN), Laval University, Quebec City, QC, Canada; Smol, J.P., Paleoecological Environmental Assessment and Research Lab (PEARL), Department of Biology, Queen's University, Kingston, ON, Canada","Climate change is generating complex responses in both natural and human ecosystems that vary in their geographic distribution, magnitude, and timing across the global landscape. One of the major issues that scientists and policy makers now confront is how to assess such massive changes over multiple scales of space and time. Lakes and reservoirs comprise a geographically distributed network of the lowest points in the surrounding landscape that make them important sentinels of climate change. Their physical, chemical, and biological responses to climate provide a variety of information-rich signals. Their sediments archive and integrate these signals, enabling paleolimnologists to document changes over years to millennia. Lakes are also hot spots of carbon cycling in the landscape and as such are important regulators of climate change, processing terrestrial and atmospheric as well as aquatic carbon. We provide an overview of this concept of lakes and reservoirs as sentinels, integrators, and regulators of climate change, as well as of the need for scaling and modeling these responses in the context of global climate change. We conclude by providing a brief look to the future and the creation of globally networked sensors in lakes and reservoirs around the world. © 2009, by the American Society of Limnology and Oceanography, Inc.",,"biological analysis; carbon cycle; climate change; future prospect; geographical distribution; physicochemical property; policy making; reservoir; spatiotemporal analysis",,,,,,"Adrian, R., Lakes as sentinels of current climate change (2009) Limnol. Oceanogr., 54, pp. 2283-2297; Antoniades, D., Bacterial dominance of phototrophic communities in a High Arctic lake and its implications for paleoclimate analysis Polar Sci, , In press; Austin, J.A., Colman, S.M., Lake Superior summer water temperatures are increasing more rapidly than regional temperatures: A positive ice-albedo feedback (2007) Geophysical Research Letters, 34 (6), pp. L06604. , DOI 10.1029/2006GL029021; Beaugrand, G., Edwards, M., Brander, K., Luczak, C., Ibanez, F., Causes and projections of abrupt climate-driven ecosystem shifts in the North Atlantic (2008) Ecol. Lett., 11, pp. 1157-1168; Bradley, R.S., Vuille, M., Diaz, H.F., Vergara, W., Threats to water supplies in the tropical Andes (2006) Science, 312, pp. 1755-1756; Brooks, A.S., Zastrow, J.C., The potential influence of climate change on offshore primary production in Lake Michigan (2002) J. Great Lakes Res., 28, pp. 597-607; Castañeda, I.S., Werne, J.P., Johnson, T.C., Influence of climate change on algal community structure and primary productivity of Lake Malawi (East Africa) from the Last Glacial Maximum to present (2009) Limnol. Oceanogr., 54, pp. 2431-2447; Catalan, J., Pla, S., Garcia, J., Camarero, L., Climate and CO2 saturation in an alpine l